<Base
  title="How We Research"
  description="Our sourcing standards: the difference between firsthand bench diagnoses and researched entries, and how each is labelled."
>
  <div class="wrap page-body">
    <p class="kicker" style="margin-top: 2rem;">Sourcing standards</p>
    <h1>How We Research</h1>

    <p>
      Every entry on ToolFaultFinder is labelled with one of two source types, shown on the
      entry's quick-facts plate. The label tells you exactly how much weight to give it.
    </p>

    <h2><span class="tag tag-firsthand">firsthand</span>&ensp;We had it on the bench</h2>
    <p>
      A firsthand entry means we physically had the tool, reproduced the fault, and performed
      the diagnosis ourselves. Multimeter readings, teardown observations, and part numbers in
      these entries come from the actual repair, not from a manual. Where we made a wrong call
      during diagnosis, we say so — the dead ends are often as useful as the fix.
    </p>

    <h2><span class="tag tag-researched">researched</span>&ensp;Compiled from sources</h2>
    <p>
      A researched entry means we have <em>not</em> personally repaired that fault. Instead
      we've compiled and cross-checked information from service manuals, manufacturer
      documentation, repair forums, and teardown videos. Researched entries always list their
      sources in the quick-facts plate, and we only publish when multiple independent sources
      agree on the diagnosis.
    </p>

    <h2>What we won't do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Publish a researched entry based on a single forum post or a single video.</li>
      <li>Present researched content as firsthand experience.</li>
      <li>Recommend bypassing safety interlocks, guards, or thermal protection — ever.</li>
      <li>Pad entries with generic advice to hit a word count.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Corrections</h2>
    <p>
      If you've repaired the same fault and found something different, we want to hear it.
      Send details via the <a href="/contact/">contact form</a> — firsthand corrections from
      readers are how researched entries get upgraded or fixed.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
